The paper discusses security protocols and their evolution in the context of computer networks, physical sensors, and social networks. It proposes a new discipline of programming global behaviors through local constraints, which is relevant to the sub-category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also mentions the interlacing of computer networks with social networks, which suggests a connection to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The use of actor-networks as a formal model of computation in heterogeneous networks of computers and humans points towards the sub-category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the engineering concepts and techniques of computer security, which is relevant to the sub-category of software engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the paper mentions the emergence of a new discipline of programming, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cybernetics (cs.CY).
